The Trojan Horse of Europe
BERKELEY – Europe will have no choice but to bail out Greece.
Emergency funds will have to be provided.
Conditions will have to be attached to them.
The Greek government will make the usual promises.
This should allow the Greek government to serve its debt.
Markets will calm down.
The long-term consequences will not be deterrent, but there will be future problems.
Some will say that the fatal mistake was allowing Greece to adopt the euro first.
It was already evident, however, that the country was not ready.
Its budgetary policy was already out of control when it joined the monetary union in 2001, and its unions were already putting pressure on Greek wages to align with those practiced in Europe, despite a productivity lag.
But this answer is too simplistic, in that such signs of malfunction are not limited to Greece.
Spain, with an unemployment rate of 20% and abyssal budget deficits, sees Greece as an image of its own future.
And if that's not the case, the markets take care of it.
Portugal and Italy do a bit better.
These countries, just like Greece, must face strong budget cuts.
Like Greece, they cannot devalue their currency to encourage exports.
Like Greece, they must face a deep recession.
Like Greece, they will be tempted to ask for aid.
All of this poses only one question: was the true error not having created the euro?
In the measure that I was one of the rare Americans encouraging the idea of a European currency, you would be right to ask me: are you reconsidering your initial position?
My answer is no, the creation of the euro has not been an error, but it could well become one.
The Greek crisis shows that Europe is only halfway on the path to a viable monetary union.
If it does nothing, the next crisis could well make this one seem like a stroll in the park.
If it wants to complete its monetary union, Europe will have to create its own emergency financing mechanism.
Today, EU members can only lend their aid to Greece by circumventing the regulation that prevents them from granting a loan, except in the case of natural disasters or circumstances beyond a country's control.
This adds to the uncertainty.
When European leaders provide aid, public opinion and markets tend to question their honesty.
If the problems result from the Lisbon Treaty, then it needs to be modified.
Furthermore, aid should not be granted solely under certain conditions, but should be accompanied by a temporary national budget control by a committee of 'experts' appointed by the European Union.
The story shows us that simple promises made by beneficiary countries are not enough.
Of course, countries that will be subject to such measures will express their indignation.
But, nobody forces them to accept this money.
Moral considerations?
Here is your solution.
Notice that this would be a more effective disciplinary mechanism than the defunct Pact of Stability and Growth.
One might also ask the following question: how would Californians react if their State temporarily handed its budget over to an expert named specifically by President Barack Obama's administration?
In fact, it would not bother them that much.
The expert would not be of Californian origin, but American.
The public opinion would understand that he would act in the interest of the State of California as well as that of the country.
The fact that California sends representatives to Washington, from which orders of this expert would emanate, would reassure them.
Europeans do not do things like this because they consider themselves above all as Greeks and Germans.
They do not interfere with the "sovereignty prerogatives" of other member states.
Germany is particularly reluctant due to its history during World War II, especially in Greece.
If Europe really wants to achieve its monetary union, it must overcome its past.
This union implies not only stronger economic links, but also closer political links.
Those who have a solid emergency aid mechanism will really have to account.
They will have to answer to a strong European Parliament.
The electorate of German Chancellor Angela Merkel hates this kind of saving because they know very well who will be responsible.
Germans oppose anything resembling European political integration.
But Germany has its share of responsibility in this crisis.
It wanted an incredibly independent central bank that is not required to account, but which today has adopted a monetary policy that is too excessive, thus seriously aggravating the situation of the PIIGS (Portugal, Ireland, Italy, Greece and Spain).
The enormous current surpluses of Germany are exacerbating their situation even further.
Furthermore, its fiscal stimulus measures have not been sufficient to support the European economy.
Germany has benefited consistently from the creation of the euro.
She should give as good as she gets.
She should encourage the creation of an emergency loan facility, as well as political integration to make it possible.
She must provide more budgetary support.
Isn't she in the best position to exert pressure for a more responsible European Central Bank?
The Greek crisis could be the Trojan horse that would lead Europe towards a more accomplished political integration.
One can only hope for that.
